The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Bengal | Midnapore bandh
                                                                                                                     4                                                                                      Midnapore bandh
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                              
	Jhargram, Dec. 12: Schools, banks and shops were shut and a vegetable truck was burnt in West Midnapore during a 24-hour bandh called by the Peoples Committee Against Police Atrocities today.        
	The Maoist-backed outfits bandh comes two days after an incident of police firing that killed a villager.        
	West Midnapore superintendent of police Manoj Verma said: The bandh called today affected several parts of West Midnapore. They (the committee supporters) tried to create trouble in some areas and succeeded in setting a truck ablaze on National Highway 6. However, the joint forces were alert today and were present in large numbers.        
	The peoples committee supporters stopped the truck carrying vegetables near Jhargram and set it on fire around 9am, holding up highway traffic for over an hour.         
	The truck was set on fire on NH 6, linking Calcutta and Mumbai, at Mohanpur. Around 30 PCPA men with arms stopped the vehicle and yanked the driver and helper out before burning the truck, said a police officer.                                                                                                                                                             
